Exercise 14.41: Why do you suppose the new standard added lambdas?
Explain when you would use a lambda and when you would write a class
instead

Answer:
I think the new standard added lambdas for a one time function, instead of writing a class from scratch for a single call
a lambda function will do that, when calling a class more then a few times it is better to write the class itself.

Exercise 14.42: Using library function objects and adaptors, define an
expression to
(a) Count the number of values that are greater than 1024
(b) Find the first string that is not equal to pooh
(c) Multiply all values by 2

Answer:
std::vector<int> vec;
std::vector<std::string> vecStr;
a)std::count_if(vec.begin(), vec.end(),std::bind(std::greater<int>(),std::placeholders::_1,1024));
b)std::find_if(vecStr.begin(),vecStr.end(), std::bind(std::not_equal_to<std::string>(),std::placeholders::_1,"pooh"));
c)std::transform(vec.begin(), vec.end(),vec.begin(), std::bind(std::multiplies<int>(),std::placeholders::_1,2));

Exercise 14.43: Using library function objects, determine whether a given
int value is divisible by any element in a container of ints.

Answer:
bool isDivisble(int input)
{
    std::vector<int> vec{2,3};
    std::modulus<int> mod;
    auto reverseMod = [&](int num){return mod(num,input) == 0;};
    return std::any_of(vec.begin(),vec.end(),reverseMod);
}

Exercise 14.46: Explain whether defining these Sales_data conversion
operators is a good idea and whether they should be explicit.

Answer:
It's a bad idea to define those operators since there is no obvious single mapping between the class type and the conversion type,
if those operators are defined then they should be explicit to prevent implicit conversions.

Exercise 14.47: Explain the difference between these two conversion
operators:
struct Integral {
    operator const int(); ---> const will be ignored.
    operator int() const; ---> const is applied to the object itself which insures that the state will not be changed.
};

